The Nigeria Customs Service (NCS), Strike force, Zone ‘A’  has slammed a debit note (DN) worth N1.104 billion from importers that made false declarations on cargoes at the Lagos seaports. The DN which was slammed on the importers who have paid lesser duties across the six area commands of the service in the South West. The coordinator of the Strike force, Abba Kakudi, as assistant comptroller of customs, in a statement over the weekend, said the amount generated through the debits notes was in the last six months. According to him, the seizures were between January 1 and June 11, 2020, adding that in spite of COVID-19 pandemic, which affected movement of goods, the Strike force team were able to raise DN to the tune of N1.104 billion. Speaking on the seizures, he said in the last two weeks, the Strike Force team had given a hard chase to smugglers who were desperate to unleash economic dislocation of the country. Giving the details of the seizures, he added, “Our seizures include; 1000 bags of 50kg foreign parboiled rice with the Duty Payment Value (DPV) 13.252 million, 10 Tokunbo vehicles with DPV N31.184 million and 30 bales of second hand clothing with DPV of N2.160 million. It is important to say that in order to help the economy to grow, there is no need to import what we can produce here in Nigeria or bringing in prohibited items.” According to him, the federal government has encouraged a lot of rice farmers in the country, where local rice is being produced in large quantities and even healthier than foreign rice.  He added that traders should avail themselves of this opportunity to market our indigenous products in such a way, as to grow the economy maximally.